  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "\"6/6 myopia vision\" refers to a specific condition of eyesight, where \"6/6\" denotes normal vision acuity, but the term \"myopia\" indicates that the individual is nearsighted.\n\nTo clarify further:\n- The \"6/6\" notation is used in many countries (and is equivalent to 20/20 vision in the United States) and means that at a distance of 6 meters, a person can see what a person with normal vision can see at that distance. In other words, this measurement indicates normal visual acuity.\n- \"Myopia\" or nearsightedness means that while distant objects appear blurry, nearby objects can be seen clearly. In this context, having 6/6 vision may seem paradoxical, as myopia typically comes with reduced vision acuity for distant objects.\n\nIn the case of someone with 6/6 myopia vision, it could imply that they have myopia but have been corrected (often through glasses or contact lenses) to achieve normal visual acuity (6/6) for distance viewing. Thus, they might still be considered myopic but have the necessary correction to see clearly at a distance.",
